{
  "slug": "ida-pro-cheatsheet",
  "title": "IDA Pro Cheat Sheet",
  "subtitle": "Comprehensive IDA Pro reference for reverse engineering, navigation, renaming, analysis, and workflow.",
  "sections": [
    {
      "type": "text",
      "title": "Suggested Reverse Engineering Approach",
      "text": "1. Start broad: inspect strings, imports, exports, entry point, sections, and obvious capabilities before reading functions line by line.\n\n2. Rename aggressively: functions, globals, stack vars, structures, enums, and offsets become much easier to reason about once named.\n\n3. Work top-down first: identify main logic, argument parsing, config loading, validation gates, dispatchers, crypto/encoding loops, network/file handlers, and anti-debug checks.\n\n4. Use graph view, linear disassembly, and pseudocode together: each reveals different things. Verify decompiler output when pointer math, sign extension, switch recovery, or optimized compiler patterns look suspicious.\n\n5. Follow data flow, not just control flow: where input comes from, how it is transformed, and where it is validated or acted on.\n\n6. Build types early when possible: structs, enums, arrays, function pointers, and corrected prototypes often dramatically improve readability.\n\n7. Comment and bookmark every important landmark: compare/jump gates, unpacking routines, decryption loops, import wrappers, error handlers, allocators, and protocol parsers.\n\n8. Iterate in passes: first locate landmarks, then rename, then fix types, then reconstruct behavior."
    },
